h -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Burger King said that it had explored \"using aggregated keywords, such as common hospitality phrases\" to understand the overall service being offered and to \"recognise teams who deliver great hospitality\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"We believe hospitality is fundamentally human. The role of this technology is to support our teams so they can stay present with guests,\" the firm said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Customer service calls have routinely been recorded and monitored for years. Employees are often aware that they can be assessed to ensure they\'re using the correct language.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But this latest step by Burger King elicited swift condemnation among some social media users who described it as \"dystopian\". Others questioned how accurate the chat-bot headsets will be, given that AI tools have proven to be prone to errors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other fast-food chains have also started to explore the use of AI in its stores. Yum Brands, whose chains include Taco Bell and Pizza Hut, last year announced a partnership with the chip giant Nvidia to develop AI tools for its restaurants.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->','Burger King rolls out AI headsets that track employee \'friendliness\'','','inherit','closed','closed','','11-revision-v1','','','2026-02-27 10:25:02','2026-02-27 10:25:02','',11,'https://news.loc/?p=13',0,'revision','',0),(14,1,'2026-02-27 10:31:20','2026-02-27 10:31:20','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/624/cpsprodpb/98d2/live/756afa70-132c-11f1-8080-b36026ca95b4.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea won the first edition of the revamped Fifa Club World Cup last July, but have also beaten their rivals to the title of biggest financial losers</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Daniel Austin</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BBC Sport senior journalist</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Chelsea recorded a pre-tax loss of 355m for 2024-25, according to financial figures released by Uefa.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is the highest annual loss ever made by an English football club, and the second highest in European history, following the 484m Barcelona lost in 2021.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So what is the detail behind the numbers?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Chelsea bring in less money than other wealthy PL clubs</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The report doesn\'t break down the loss into its component parts, but there are clues.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Uefa\'s figures show Chelsea\'s overall revenue was significantly lower than some of their Premier League rivals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Blues brought in 511m, compared to 746m for Manchester City and 744m for Liverpool.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That difference comes from a few key areas.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea\'s income from ticket sales was the ninth-highest in Europe but still 28m less than Liverpool, one place ahead of them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The average amount Chelsea made per matchday was 1.2m less than Liverpool, who again were one spot ahead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea\'s matchday revenue is restricted by the capacity of Stamford Bridge, which at 41,798 is only the 11th-biggest ground in the Premier League, 34,000 smaller than Manchester United\'s Old Trafford.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Blues also made far less in commercial revenue than some of their rivals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>They were ranked 11th for commercial revenue in Europe last year, making 207m - 5m down on the previous year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That puts their commercial revenue 66m lower than Tottenham - the next-highest English club - and 165m lower than Manchester City, who brought in more than anyone else in the Premier League.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea also made far less from merchandising and kit sales than the five other wealthiest Premier League clubs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>They generated 83m from that revenue stream - no improvement on the previous year. That is 46m less than Spurs and 82m less than top-ranked Manchester United.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The only area in which Chelsea performed impressively in comparison to their rivals was broadcast revenue, with participation and victory in the Fifa Club World Cup boosting income to 192m, putting them second-highest on the list in Europe, behind Manchester City.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/976/cpsprodpb/e62c/live/66431c10-1333-11f1-ba29-8dbbd227222d.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea chairman Todd Boehly has previously defended the club\'s financial approach</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->','How have Chelsea made biggest loss in English football history?','','publish','closed','closed','','how-have-chelsea-made-biggest-loss-in-english-football-history','','','2026-02-27 10:55:25','2026-02-27 10:55:25','',0,'https://news.loc/?p=14',0,'post','',0),(15,1,'2026-02-27 10:31:20','2026-02-27 10:31:20','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/624/cpsprodpb/98d2/live/756afa70-132c-11f1-8080-b36026ca95b4.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea won the first edition of the revamped Fifa Club World Cup last July, but have also beaten their rivals to the title of biggest financial losers</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Daniel Austin</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BBC Sport senior journalist</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Chelsea recorded a pre-tax loss of 355m for 2024-25, according to financial figures released by Uefa.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is the highest annual loss ever made by an English football club, and the second highest in European history, following the 484m Barcelona lost in 2021.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So what is the detail behind the numbers?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Chelsea bring in less money than other wealthy PL clubs</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The report doesn\'t break down the loss into its component parts, but there are clues.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Uefa\'s figures show Chelsea\'s overall revenue was significantly lower than some of their Premier League rivals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Blues brought in 511m, compared to 746m for Manchester City and 744m for Liverpool.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That difference comes from a few key areas.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea\'s income from ticket sales was the ninth-highest in Europe but still 28m less than Liverpool, one place ahead of them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The average amount Chelsea made per matchday was 1.2m less than Liverpool, who again were one spot ahead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea\'s matchday revenue is restricted by the capacity of Stamford Bridge, which at 41,798 is only the 11th-biggest ground in the Premier League, 34,000 smaller than Manchester United\'s Old Trafford.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Blues also made far less in commercial revenue than some of their rivals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>They were ranked 11th for commercial revenue in Europe last year, making 207m - 5m down on the previous year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That puts their commercial revenue 66m lower than Tottenham - the next-highest English club - and 165m lower than Manchester City, who brought in more than anyone else in the Premier League.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea also made far less from merchandising and kit sales than the five other wealthiest Premier League clubs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>They generated 83m from that revenue stream - no improvement on the previous year. That is 46m less than Spurs and 82m less than top-ranked Manchester United.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The only area in which Chelsea performed impressively in comparison to their rivals was broadcast revenue, with participation and victory in the Fifa Club World Cup boosting income to 192m, putting them second-highest on the list in Europe, behind Manchester City.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/976/cpsprodpb/e62c/live/66431c10-1333-11f1-ba29-8dbbd227222d.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chelsea chairman Todd Boehly has previously defended the club\'s financial approach</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->','How have Chelsea made biggest loss in English football history?','','inherit','closed','closed','','14-revision-v1','','','2026-02-27 10:31:20','2026-02-27 10:31:20','',14,'https://news.loc/?p=15',0,'revision','',0),(16,1,'2026-02-27 10:36:03','2026-02-27 10:36:03','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/800/cpsprodpb/4971/live/4c573090-117e-11f1-ae0b-bf8115d77a66.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"fontSize\":\"regular\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-regular-font-size\">Floyd Mayweather, then 38, outpointed Manny Pacquiao, then 36, in their 2015 world title fight</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\",\"justifyContent\":\"left\",\"flexWrap\":\"wrap\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Coral Barry</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"layout\":{\"selfStretch\":\"fit\",\"flexSize\":null}}} -->\n<p>Combat Sports Senior Journalist</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"24px\"}}} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>Floyd Mayweather, 49, and Manny Pacquiao, 47, will contest their</strong><a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/sport/boxing/articles/c9v0degnx04o\"><strong>rematch in a professional bout</strong></a><strong>in Las Vegas on 19 September.</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is a weird fight, \"a carnival\" as Steve Bunce aptly puts it. It is not one that boxing fans have been clamouring for. Nor were they ever considering how the first fight went in 2015  delivered five years too late and as stale as feared.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Carnival\" boxing events, however, have become Netflix\'s trademark. The streaming platform values one-off, big impact fights that may have little shelf life but burn bright in the moment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"It\'s not the first carnival fight on Netflix,\" 5 Live Boxing expert Bunce told 5 Live Breakfast.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"We\'ve had Mike Tyson against Jake Paul. We\'ve had Jake Paul against Anthony Joshua.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"We\'re so far down the freak fight road that this one doesn\'t actually raise any alarms bells.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"It\'ll just be two men, way past their best in a legitimate fight that is nothing more than an ego-driven sparring session.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"This circus just gets deeper and deeper and deeper.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','\'Equal in decay\' - Mayweather v Pacquiao is another boxing \'carnival\'','','publish','closed','closed','','equal-in-decay-mayweather-v-pacquiao-is-another-boxing-carnival','','','2026-02-27 10:55:20','2026-02-27 10:55:20','',0,'https://news.loc/?p=16',0,'post','',0),(17,1,'2026-02-27 10:36:03','2026-02-27 10:36:03','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/800/cpsprodpb/4971/live/4c573090-117e-11f1-ae0b-bf8115d77a66.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"fontSize\":\"regular\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-regular-font-size\">Floyd Mayweather, then 38, outpointed Manny Pacquiao, then 36, in their 2015 world title fight</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\",\"justifyContent\":\"left\",\"flexWrap\":\"wrap\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Coral Barry</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"layout\":{\"selfStretch\":\"fit\",\"flexSize\":null}}} -->\n<p>Combat Sports Senior Journalist</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"24px\"}}} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>Floyd Mayweather, 49, and Manny Pacquiao, 47, will contest their</strong><a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/sport/boxing/articles/c9v0degnx04o\"><strong>rematch in a professional bout</strong></a><strong>in Las Vegas on 19 September.</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is a weird fight, \"a carnival\" as Steve Bunce aptly puts it. It is not one that boxing fans have been clamouring for. Nor were they ever considering how the first fight went in 2015  delivered five years too late and as stale as feared.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Carnival\" boxing events, however, have become Netflix\'s trademark. The streaming platform values one-off, big impact fights that may have little shelf life but burn bright in the moment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"It\'s not the first carnival fight on Netflix,\" 5 Live Boxing expert Bunce told 5 Live Breakfast.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"We\'ve had Mike Tyson against Jake Paul. We\'ve had Jake Paul against Anthony Joshua.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"We\'re so far down the freak fight road that this one doesn\'t actually raise any alarms bells.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"It\'ll just be two men, way past their best in a legitimate fight that is nothing more than an ego-driven sparring session.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"This circus just gets deeper and deeper and deeper.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','\'Equal in decay\' - Mayweather v Pacquiao is another boxing \'carnival\'','','inherit','closed','closed','','16-revision-v1','','','2026-02-27 10:36:03','2026-02-27 10:36:03','',16,'https://news.loc/?p=17',0,'revision','',0),(18,1,'2026-02-27 10:37:38','2026-02-27 10:37:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember the textbook story of&nbsp;2017? Then, the unremarkable beverage company Long Island Iced Tea suddenly changed its name to&nbsp;Long Blockchain Corp. Their shares instantly soared 200%, although the business model remained the same&nbsp; selling sweet water. The market was not buying the product, the market was buying the hype word.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://dev.ua/storage/images/42/15/14/94/derived/b4cb9d9ff44e7134eb804722690f575b.jpg\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Today, in&nbsp;2026, we&nbsp;are witnessing the reincarnation of&nbsp;this absurdity. Only now the magic spell has changed: instead of&nbsp;Blockchain, everyone is&nbsp;plastering the facade with the sign AI.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As&nbsp;soon as&nbsp;an&nbsp;unknown token adds the prefix GPT, Neural or&nbsp;simply AI to&nbsp;its ticker, its capitalization begins to&nbsp;defy the laws of&nbsp;gravity (and common sense). Investors, frightened by&nbsp;the success of&nbsp;NVIDIA and OpenAI, are afraid to&nbsp;miss the next big trend and are pouring money into anything that even remotely resembles a&nbsp;neural network.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As&nbsp;COO of&nbsp;the specialized media outlet&nbsp;<a href=\"http://incrypted/\">Incrypted</a>, which processes dozens of&nbsp;press releases and pitch decks every day, Andriy Makarov sees the flip side of&nbsp;this rally. Artificial intelligence is&nbsp;certainly a&nbsp;technological revolution comparable to&nbsp;the invention of&nbsp;the Internet. But 90% of&nbsp;so-called AI&nbsp;tokens have the same relationship to&nbsp;this revolution as&nbsp;the RGB backlight on&nbsp;an&nbsp;old office laptop has to&nbsp;its performance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In&nbsp;this column, he&nbsp;suggests putting aside the emotions of&nbsp;FOMO (fear of&nbsp;missing out) and figuring out where in&nbsp;the AI-Crypto sector is&nbsp;the real infrastructure on&nbsp;which the economy of&nbsp;the future will be&nbsp;built, and where is&nbsp;it&nbsp;just a&nbsp;nice wrapper for selling air.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">AI-Wrappers, or&nbsp;Marketing Dust</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If&nbsp;we&nbsp;look under the hood of&nbsp;most projects that are flooding the market today, we&nbsp;will see not revolutionary technology, but banal arbitrage.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The scheme looks painfully simple: the development team takes an&nbsp;API from OpenAI (ChatGPT) or&nbsp;Anthropic (Claude), wraps it&nbsp;into a&nbsp;convenient interface (for example, a&nbsp;Telegram bot or&nbsp;a&nbsp;web application), adds a&nbsp;picture generation function and issues its own token. In&nbsp;Pitch Deck, it&nbsp;is&nbsp;called Next-Generation Decentralized AI&nbsp;Assistant. In&nbsp;reality, it&nbsp;is&nbsp;a&nbsp;resale of&nbsp;someone elses product with a&nbsp;markup.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here the main question arises that kills 99% of&nbsp;such startups: Why blockchain?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If&nbsp;your product is&nbsp;a&nbsp;chatbot, why should a&nbsp;user buy a&nbsp;volatile token, pay network fees, and deal with a&nbsp;wallet when they can simply pay for the subscription with a&nbsp;bank card for $20? The answer is&nbsp;cynical but honest: the token here is&nbsp;not for the product. The token here is&nbsp;a&nbsp;casino ticket.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It&nbsp;doesnt solve any technological problem. It&nbsp;exists only so&nbsp;that founders can raise capital on&nbsp;the wave of&nbsp;hype, and early investors can cash in&nbsp;on&nbsp;retail users. Such projects are caliphs for an&nbsp;hour. Their business model lives exactly until the moment when OpenAI releases another update that makes their unique functionality a&nbsp;free basic feature.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">DePIN and Iron&nbsp; where the real money is&nbsp;hidden</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If&nbsp;we&nbsp;strip away all the marketing noise, we&nbsp;see the one area where blockchain is&nbsp;vital to&nbsp;AI&nbsp;today. Its not images or&nbsp;chatbots. Its resources.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Training modern neural networks requires enormous computing power. The world is&nbsp;experiencing a&nbsp;chip shortage: queues for NVIDIA H100 graphics cards are drawn a&nbsp;year in&nbsp;advance, and cloud giants like AWS or&nbsp;Google Cloud are raising prices sky-high. Startups simply have nowhere to&nbsp;train their models.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is&nbsp;where&nbsp;<a href=\"https://incrypted.com/ua/shcho-take-depin/\">DePIN</a>&nbsp;(Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Networks) comes&nbsp;in. Its essentially the Airbnb for graphics cards.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Imagine millions of&nbsp;gaming PCs around the world sitting idle for 20 hours a&nbsp;day. Or&nbsp;data centers with empty slots. Crypto projects (such as&nbsp;Render, io.net, Akash, and others) are pooling these disparate capacities into a&nbsp;single network and renting them out to&nbsp;AI&nbsp;developers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whats the magic here?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cheaper: Itcosts many times less than Amazon because ituses existing hardware.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>More accessible: Nocorporate censorship (noone will shut you down for training the wrong model).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Token Economy: Here, the token isnot acasino ticket, but areal means ofpayment. The developer buys the token topay for the GPU rental. The owner ofthe graphics card receives the token aspayment for the work.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is&nbsp;a&nbsp;classic, understandable business model: there is&nbsp;demand (AI&nbsp;companies), there is&nbsp;supply (GPU owners), and there is&nbsp;blockchain as&nbsp;an&nbsp;ideal mechanism for settlements between them. It&nbsp;is&nbsp;here, at&nbsp;the junction of&nbsp;hardware and code, that real unicorns are born, not one-day memes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Black Box Problem: When Eyes Lie, Blockchain Tells the Truth</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As&nbsp;the COO of&nbsp;a&nbsp;media resource, I&nbsp;face a&nbsp;problem every day that seemed like a&nbsp;dystopian plot just yesterday. We&nbsp;live in&nbsp;a&nbsp;world where a&nbsp;video message from the president about surrender can be&nbsp;generated in&nbsp;10 minutes, and the voice of&nbsp;the CEO of&nbsp;a&nbsp;major stock exchange can be&nbsp;faked so&nbsp;that even your own mother cant tell the difference.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Artificial intelligence has created a&nbsp;paradox: content has become infinitely abundant, but trust in&nbsp;it&nbsp;has fallen to&nbsp;zero. In&nbsp;this reality, Dont Trust, Verify ceases to&nbsp;be&nbsp;just a&nbsp;slogan of&nbsp;cypherpunks. It&nbsp;becomes the only way for the information space to&nbsp;survive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And here cryptography is&nbsp;a&nbsp;natural antidote to&nbsp;AI. Blockchain could become a&nbsp;global notary for the internet. Imagine a&nbsp;technology of&nbsp;digital watermarks that cannot be&nbsp;erased or&nbsp;forged.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When a&nbsp;journalist publishes a&nbsp;story, it&nbsp;is&nbsp;signed with their cryptographic key on&nbsp;the blockchain. When a&nbsp;neural network generates an&nbsp;image, this fact is&nbsp;recorded in&nbsp;metadata recorded on&nbsp;the chain.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is&nbsp;not about tokens or&nbsp;native. This is&nbsp;about Provenance (data origin). We&nbsp;are moving towards browsers and social networks automatically labeling content:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Green check mark: Signed Encrypted. Original.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Red flag: Source unknown. Probably AIgenerated.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Projects that build&nbsp;<a href=\"https://incrypted.com/ua/blokchejn-agenty-ta-roboty/\">the infrastructure</a>&nbsp;for such content verification are the third pillar of&nbsp;real value. They sell not hype, but truth. And truth in&nbsp;the era of&nbsp;deepfakes will cost a&nbsp;lot.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Conclusion: How not to&nbsp;buy air instead of&nbsp;technology</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Artificial intelligence is&nbsp;the new electricity. Blockchain is&nbsp;the new rails for its accounting and transmission. Their intersection will inevitably give rise to&nbsp;new technological giants on&nbsp;the scale of&nbsp;Google or&nbsp;Amazon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But as&nbsp;we&nbsp;move towards this bright future, we&nbsp;will have to&nbsp;wade through the swamp of&nbsp;hype. In&nbsp;order not to&nbsp;drown your investments in&nbsp;yet another AI&nbsp;memecoin, I&nbsp;offer a&nbsp;simple filter that I&nbsp;use myself when looking at&nbsp;new projects.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Checklist: 3 questions for an&nbsp;AI&nbsp;project</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Visa/Mastercard Test: Does this project need its own token tofunction? Ifaservice (e.g. image generation) can beeasily paid for with aregular bank card, and the token isattached tothe side asaloyalty program, thats ared flag. Inreal Web3 projects, the token isthe fuel (Gas) for the network, without which itwill stop.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The Wrapper Test: Does the team have its own technology? Ask directly: What does your AImodel run on? Ifthe answer isvague orboils down toweuse the APIs ofmarket leaders, youre not dealing with atechnology startup, but anintermediary. Intermediaries dont last long inIT.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Money Test: Where does the project plan tomake money? Ifthe business model isbased onselling tokens toretail investors, rather than selling services toB2B clients, its apyramid scheme with AIelements. Look for those who make money from fees for computing, hardware rental, ordata verification.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dont let the pretty acronyms blind&nbsp;you. The market will clear. The wrappers will disappear as&nbsp;quickly as&nbsp;thousands of&nbsp;ICO projects disappeared in&nbsp;2018. Only those who build the roads (infrastructure) will remain, not those who just stand on&nbsp;the side of&nbsp;the road with a&nbsp;bright AI poster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','AI Tokens: Real Value or Just a New Hype Label','','publish','closed','closed','','ai-tokens-real-value-or-just-a-new-hype-label','','','2026-02-27 10:55:15','2026-02-27 10:55:15','',0,'https://news.loc/?p=18',0,'post','',0),(19,1,'2026-02-27 10:37:38','2026-02-27 10:37:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember the textbook story of2017? Then, the unremarkable beverage company Long Island Iced Tea suddenly changed its name toLong Blockchain Corp. Their shares instantly soared 200%, although the business model remained the same selling sweet water. The market was not buying the product, the market was buying the hype word.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','AI Tokens: Real Value or Just a New Hype Label','','inherit','closed','closed','','18-revision-v1','','','2026-02-27 10:37:38','2026-02-27 10:37:38','',18,'https://news.loc/?p=19',0,'revision','',0),(20,1,'2026-02-27 10:37:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2026-02-27 10:37:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://news.loc/?p=20',0,'post','',0),(21,1,'2026-02-27 10:39:41','2026-02-27 10:39:41','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember the textbook story of&nbsp;2017? Then, the unremarkable beverage company Long Island Iced Tea suddenly changed its name to&nbsp;Long Blockchain Corp. Their shares instantly soared 200%,